<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="551" type="holotype">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">Holotype.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">
BMNH 2007.5.20.1. Male, 9.0 mm SL. Red Sea, Egypt, Hurghada, reef lagoon, 
<geoCoordinate degrees="27.285" direction="north" orientation="latitude" precision="55" value="27.285">27.285°N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate degrees="33.772778" direction="east" orientation="longitude" precision="1" value="33.772778">33.772778°E</geoCoordinate>
. 05 February 2005, M. Abu El-Regal.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
A member of the SDF group of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ahnelt &amp; Robitzch &amp; El-Regal" authorityYear="2022" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Schindleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Schindleria" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">Schindleria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which can be distinguished from all members of the LDF group by the combination of following characters (i) length of dorsal fin nearly equal to that of anal fin (vs. dorsal fin significantly longer than anal fin); (ii) body deeper (10.8% in SL vs. 4.5-5.4% in SL); (iii) body depth significantly increasing from pectoral-fin base to 4th anal-fin ray (vs. not or only slightly increasing); (iv) head short and wide with steep profile (vs. elongated and narrow with flat profile) and (v) both jaws toothless (vs. both jaws with teeth).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">
From the other species of the SDF group, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ahnelt &amp; Robitzch &amp; El-Regal" authorityYear="2022" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Schindleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Schindleria edentata" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="edentata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">Schindleria edentata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished as follows 15 dorsal-fin rays (vs. 9-13 in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. parva" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. brevipinguis" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="brevipinguis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. brevipinguis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 16-18 in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. pietschmanni" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="pietschmanni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. pietschmanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), 13 anal-fin rays (vs. 7-11 in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. parva" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. brevipinguis" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="brevipinguis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. brevipinguis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 19-21 in S. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schindler" baseAuthorityYear="1931" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Schindleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Schindleria pietschmanni" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pietschmanni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">Schindleria pietschmanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), preanal-fin length 64.8 % SL (vs. 72% in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. parva" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 66.7% in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. brevipinguis" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="brevipinguis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. brevipinguis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 54% in S. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schindler" baseAuthorityYear="1931" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Schindleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Schindleria pietschmanni" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pietschmanni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">Schindleria pietschmanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), predorsal-fin length 60.9% SL (vs. 65.0% in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. parva" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 63.0% in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. brevipinguis" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="brevipinguis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. brevipinguis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 58.3% in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. pietschmanni" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="pietschmanni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. pietschmanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); length of tail excluding caudal fin 36.2% SL (vs. 28.2% in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. parva" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 39.4% in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. brevipinguis" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="brevipinguis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. brevipinguis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 42.1% in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. pietschmanni" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="pietschmanni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. pietschmanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), length of urogenital papilla 4.8% SL (vs. 3.0% in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. parva" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 7.6% in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. brevipinguis" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="brevipinguis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. brevipinguis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and &lt;0.5% in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. pietschmanni" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="pietschmanni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. pietschmanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), eye diameter 27.7% HL vs. 20.0% in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. parva" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 31.1% in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. brevipinguis" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="brevipinguis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. brevipinguis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 23.1% in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. pietschmanni" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="pietschmanni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. pietschmanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), mouth terminal (vs. superior in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. parva" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. pietschmanni" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="pietschmanni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. pietschmanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. brevipinguis" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="brevipinguis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. brevipinguis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ahnelt &amp; Robitzch &amp; El-Regal" authorityYear="2022" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Schindleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Schindleria edentata" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="edentata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">Schindleria edentata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be further distinguished from 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. brevipinguis" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="brevipinguis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. brevipinguis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. pietschmanni" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="pietschmanni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. pietschmanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by a wider head (35.9% HL vs. 55.7% in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. brevipinguis" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="brevipinguis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. brevipinguis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 43.2% in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. pietschmanni" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="pietschmanni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. pietschmanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and a lower number of caudal procurrent rays (4/4 vs. 6/6 in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. brevipinguis" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="brevipinguis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. brevipinguis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. pietschmanni" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="pietschmanni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. pietschmanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ahnelt &amp; Robitzch &amp; El-Regal" authorityYear="2022" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Schindleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Schindleria edentata" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="edentata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">Schindleria edentata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be further distinguished from 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. parva" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. pietschmanni" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="pietschmanni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. pietschmanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its toothless jaws (vs. upper jaw toothed in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. parva" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
both jaws toothed in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. pietschmanni" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="pietschmanni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. pietschmanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and head shape (stubby, oval with steep profile vs. elongated, narrow with flat profile in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. parva" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. pietschmanni" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="pietschmanni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. pietschmanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ahnelt &amp; Robitzch &amp; El-Regal" authorityYear="2022" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Schindleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Schindleria edentata" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="edentata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">Schindleria edentata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be further distinguished from 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. parva" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by fewer myomeres (36 vs. 39), the first dorsal-fin inserted at myomere 21 (vs. myomere 24), the first anal-fin ray at myomere 23 (vs. myomere 26) and a greater body depth at pectoral-fin base (7.3% SL vs. 5%).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ahnelt &amp; Robitzch &amp; El-Regal" authorityYear="2022" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Schindleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Schindleria edentata" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="edentata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">Schindleria edentata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be further distinguished from 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. brevipinguis" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" rank="species" species="brevipinguis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">S. brevipinguis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by a shorter caudal peduncle (8.2% SL vs. 11.5%), pectoral-radial plate longer than wide (vs. nearly as long as wide) and a pigmented swim bladder (vs. unpigmented swim-bladder).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="551" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">
Morphometric information for the holotype is given in Table 
<tableCitation captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="T1" captionText="Table 1. Body proportions in % of standard length of holotype of Schindleria edentata sp. nov., BMNH 2007.5.20.1 and males of the two other dwarf species, S. brevipinguis, AMS-I- 26323 - 003 and S. parva, SMF 38021. Data for S. parva were calculated from measurements in Abu El-Regal et al. (2021) (Table 1). Differences between S. edentata and other species highlighted in grey. * TL from Abu El-Regal and Kon (2008)." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/2E1D332F518A37DEC49180A78CEC610B" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" tableUuid="2E1D332F518A37DEC49180A78CEC610B">1</tableCitation>
and meristic data in Table 
<tableCitation captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="T2" captionText="Table 2. Meristic information for holotype of Schindleria edentata sp. nov., BMNH 2007.5.20.1 and males of the two other dwarf species S. brevipinguis, AMS-I- 26323 - 003 and S. parva, SMF 38021. Data for S. parva from Abu El-Regal et al. (2021) (Table 1). Differences between S. edentata and other species highlighted in grey. d = damaged. * Data from Abu El-Regal and Kon (2008)." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/C4F02EFA670C3283735C17CD99404B00" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" tableUuid="C4F02EFA670C3283735C17CD99404B00">2</tableCitation>
. Body elongate, increases gradually in depth from about myomere 8 to about middle of tail, rapidly decreasing in depth to end in long narrow caudal peduncle, length ca. 25% of SL); head oval with steep profile; snout short, rounded; jaws short, reaching below origin of eye; lower jaw curved towards midline (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Holotype of Schindleria edentata (BMNH 2007.5.20.1), male, SL 9.0 mm; head in lateral view. Scale bar = 0.2 mm. Photo H. Ahnelt." figureDoi="10.3897/vz.72.e79401.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/717062" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/vz.72.e79401.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/717062" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" start="Figure 2" startId="F2">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">Figure 2.</emphasis>
Holotype of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ahnelt &amp; Robitzch &amp; El-Regal" authorityYear="2022" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Schindleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Schindleria edentata" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="edentata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">Schindleria edentata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(BMNH 2007.5.20.1), male, SL 9.0 mm; head in lateral view. Scale bar = 0.2 mm. Photo H. Ahnelt.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">First dorsal fin and pelvic fin absent; dorsal-fin rays 15; anal-fin rays 13; pectoral-fin rays 14; principle caudal-fin rays 7+6=13; caudal fin truncated; procurrent rays 4 dorsal and 4 ventral; procurrent rays gradually increasing in length, last procurrent ray simple, with no additional spine, not distinctly elongated; base of first dorsal-fin ray at myomere 21, that of last dorsal-fin ray at myomere 35; base of first anal-fin ray at myomere 22, that of last anal-fin ray at myomere 35; total number of myomeres 36 with 21 abdominal and 15 caudal; vertebrae 37,with 21 abdominal and 16 caudal (incl. urostyle); Branchiostegal rays 5; pectoral-radial plate longer than wide, of paddle-like shape, narrow at origin and wide distally; gut straight; male urogenital papilla elongated, tubular, tapering towards posteriorly curved tip, tip without distinct lobes at opening; swim bladder small, inconspicuous, pigmented dorsally, located at myomere 13, in posterior half of abdomen,.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="551" type="coloration in life">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">Coloration in life.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">
Transparent; the only pigment is a melanophore cap on top of the swim bladder and the black pigmentation of the eye (see also 
<bibRefCitation DOI="doi.org/10.111/j.1095-8649.2008.01811.x" author="Abu El-Regal, M" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Fish Biology" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" refId="B2" refString="Abu El-Regal, M, Kon, T, 2008. First record of the paedomorphic fish Schindleria (Gobioidei, Schindleriidae) from the Red Sea. Journal of Fish Biology 72: 1539-1543. htps:// doi.org/10.111/j.1095-8649.2008.01811.x" title="First record of the paedomorphic fish Schindleria (Gobioidei, Schindleriidae) from the Red Sea. Journal of Fish Biology 72: 1539 - 1543. htps: //" url="doi.org/10.111/j.1095-8649.2008.01811.x" year="2008">Abu El-Regal and Kon 2008</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="551" type="coloration preserved">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">Coloration preserved.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">
Due to subsequent preservation artifacts, the entire specimen is now dark brown to blackish (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. A Holotype of Schindleria edentata (BMNH 2007.5.20.1), male, SL 9.0 mm; Egypt, Hurghada. Arrows indicate position of broken-off first and second dorsal fin rays. Scale bar = 1 mm. Photo H. Ahnelt. B Same specimen, but photo taken shortly after initial collection. Grey arrow indicates position of last dorsal fin ray, black arrow indicates position of swim bladder. Scale = 1 mm. Photo M. Abu El-Regal." figureDoi="10.3897/vz.72.e79401.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/717061" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">1A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="551" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ahnelt &amp; Robitzch &amp; El-Regal" authorityYear="2022" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Schindleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Schindleria edentata" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="edentata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">Schindleria edentata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is only known from a shallow (7 m) reef lagoon near Hurghada (Egypt), Red Sea (
<geoCoordinate degrees="27.285" direction="north" orientation="latitude" precision="55" value="27.285">27.285°N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate degrees="33.772778" direction="east" orientation="longitude" precision="1" value="33.772778">33.772778°E</geoCoordinate>
) (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Records of Schindleria in the Red Sea. Circle = S. elongata, S. nigropunctata, Hurghada (Fricke &amp; Abu El-Regal, 2017 a, b) and S. praematura, Hurghada (Abu El-Regal and Kon 2019); black star = sampling site of S. edentata nov. spec., Hurghada; black dot = Schindleria sp., Thuwal (Robitzch et al. 2021); black square = S. parva, Jeddah (Abu El-Regal et al. 2021); empty square = Schindleria sp., Jeddah (Al-Solami and Abu El-Regal 2020). Map is based on https: // www. landkartenindex. de / kostenlos / cliparts / cliparts _ gruppe _ 1 / saudiarabien. gif" figureDoi="10.3897/vz.72.e79401.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/717063" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
