<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="551" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">Habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">The bottom of the lagoon was sandy and covered with algae and seagrass. The specimen was sampled at a depth of 1 m.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="551" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">
The name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ahnelt &amp; Robitzch &amp; El-Regal" authorityYear="2022" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Schindleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Schindleria edentata" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="edentata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">Schindleria edentata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, derived from the Latin 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">e</emphasis>
= without, and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">dentatus</emphasis>
= toothed, refers to the absence of teeth in both jaws, an adjective.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
